snippet.textDisplay: I agree, if 2019nCoV becomes a pandemic, low SES populations will be disproportionately affected. However, unlike Ebola, this virus is originating in a part of the world whose people are worldwide travelers. Hence, the vectors involved in this disease are much more complicated, and I worry about additional novel mutations. As researchers and physicians fight this epidemic, what's the end game? What does "winning" the battle against this virus look like? Vaccinations? What if it evolves into different strains? Or is the future of coronaviruses being more virulent and diverse than they've been in the past just our future outlook from now on?

snippet.textDisplay:
All I knew about this going in was that it's less of a danger than the flu and that it's an excuse for people to be racist. And that's most of what I'm taking away. Weird that you mention the face masks because I am very in favor of face masks becoming a cute fashion accessory like they are in Japan, for non-professionals to have them, so that when you do have a cold you have a way to keep others from getting sick. I feel like it's slowly becoming less of a weird thing to do and I definitely think it helps keep my cashier safe when I'm buying cold meds, my coworkers when I'm in the office, etc.


I know in an ideal world, when you have a cold, you wouldn't go to work at all, but that's not the reality that most of us live in. I'm really glad I'm not in food service anymore so I can wear a mask openly--it's counterintuitive but in food service you're often forced to come in sick, and you can't wear a face mask because who would buy food from someone who's visibly sick?

snippet.textDisplay:
Ok but specifically the comment about pets:
It depends on your pets.
Certain species (ferrets especially!!) are known for being extremely susceptible to human viruses, and while there haven't been any reported cases of them being infected, you should be taking special precautions if you have them. That doesn't mean face masks for them; if anything, you're the one who should be wearing a face mask around them! For the most part, it just means doing the same thing you're doing for yourself: wash your hands well and often, before and after handling them or cleaning any equipment or their enclosure, etc.

This also applies any time you're sick. The main thing to focus on is to keep your germs away from them.

snippet.textDisplay:
I am so thankful for this specific video; I had a cold and a flu a couple of days ago, and I have a baby and a wife. Can you imagine my horror when the Coronavirus outbreak came the way it did. I was terrified to even sleep in the same room as them. I would sleep in the toilet until almost dawn before entering the room again. And this video and the first helped me in so many ways I cant thank you enough.

Thank you for making such loving and tender caring videos that many people dont appreciate due to their ignorance.

And yes, I wanted to buy a mask so that my cold and flu wouldnt spread, but every healthcare facility I went, be it a supplier for medical instruments/equipments or just a simple clinic(they had to give me one for the sake of not spreading the virus even though they were low) to normal stores that usually sell these masks in bulk, I couldnt even get one to protect my family with. It was tragic.

But I feel safer after watching your videos and we cant thank you enough for your updates.

Stay healthy and happy :)
